	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Mar 24th 11:19 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.12]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>One of the smartest things I think someone has said here.<br><br>Yes, DKP is tedious to keep in line.&nbsp;&nbsp;You must make sure that every DKP awarded or spent has it's equal counterpart.  If not, you get A) A bunch of folks with basically no DKP or B) A bunch of folks with way way too many DKP<br><br>Of course it's hard to keep things in line.  You can't predict exactly how many DKP will be spent on a raid because the loot will not always be the same, or the loot dropped isn't worth the value of the target (IE good loot for high DKP on a low DKP easy mob or low DKP bad loot on a high DKP tough mob).  Most guilds base DKP on the potential loot a mob might drop, so that elimnates that facet.<br><br>Of course, you still can't predict how much DKP worth of loot a particular mob might drop (Tunare might drop good loot or very crappy loot as an example; her table varies from mediocre to outstanding (for velious anyway)).  I hear some system are created such that the DKP awarded for attending kills directly dictates the prices of the items as they are dropped; IE you can't make sure how much anitem will cost you have to figure out how many people showed up and were awarded DKP so you balance it.  Otherwise keeping DKP balanced dynamically but not in 'real-time' is a major headache.<br>&nbsp;<br>It is the lost who lead us through the darkest days.</td></tr>
